05056nam a22008055i 9780231548328DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018023442  a97802315483287 a10.7312/kimu189422doi  a(DE-B1597)517737  a(OCoLC)1065984246  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL872.5.I55bK5613 2019 4aPL872.5.I55bK5613 2019 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a895.63/62231 aKimura, Yūsuke, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSacred Cesium Ground and Isa's Deluge :bTwo Novellas of Japan's 3/11 Disaster /cYūsuke Kimura. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWeatherhead Books on Asia00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tSACRED CESIUM GROUND -- tISA’S DELUGE -- tTRANSLATOR’S AFTERWORD0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn these two novellas, Kimura Yūsuke explores human and animal life in northern Japan after the natural and nuclear disasters of March 11, 2011. Kimura inscribes the “Triple Disaster” into a rich regional tradition of storytelling, incorporating far-flung voices and experiences to testify to life and the desire to represent it in the aftermath of calamity.​In Sacred Cesium Ground, a woman from Tokyo travels to volunteer at a cattle farm known as the “Fortress of Hope,” tending irradiated animals abandoned after the reactor meltdown. The farm closely resembles an actual ranch that has been widely covered in Japan, and the story’s portrayal of those who stubbornly care for animals in spite of the danger speaks to the sense of futility and meaningfulness in the wake of traumatic events. Isa’s Deluge depicts a family of fishermen whose crotchety patriarch draws on old tales of the floods that have plagued the region to fashion himself as the father of the tsunami. Together, the novellas present often-unheard voices of one of Japan’s peripheral regions and their anger toward the government and Tokyo for mishandling and forgetting their part of the country. Kimura’s command of dialect and conversational language is masterfully translated by Doug Slaymaker. Postapocalyptically surreal yet teeming with life, Kimura’s stories will be a revelation for readers looking for a new perspective on the disaster’s consequences for Japan and on the interrelated meanings of human and animal lives and deaths.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aDisasterszJapanvFiction. 0aShort stories, JapanesevTranslations into English. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aSlaymaker, Doug.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz978311061036908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kimu1894240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231548328423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231548328.jpg  a978-3-11-061036-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-065195-9  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Pack